---
# ============================================================
# Baseline NetworkPolicies — cluster zero-trust
# ============================================================
# K3s enforces NetworkPolicy out of the box via its embedded kube-router
# network-policy controller (active by default alongside the Flannel CNI).
# No policies are shipped by default, so the pod network is otherwise flat:
# every pod can reach every pod, across all namespaces.
#
# This manifest installs a ZERO-TRUST cluster baseline: deny ALL ingress AND
# egress in three namespaces, then re-open only the minimal egress each system
# component needs. `kube-system` gets NO policy (see below). Application
# namespaces use the same deny-all + targeted-allow pattern — see the
# ansible-k3s README "Securing a new namespace" tutorial.
#
# Why deny-all-both here (and not just ingress)? The previous baseline left
# egress open; zero-trust closes outbound too, so a compromised pod in these
# namespaces cannot phone home or scan the storage/api networks. Each allow
# below names exactly what its component legitimately needs.
#
# What is NOT affected / NOT enforced:
#   - kube-system:  no policy at all. Its critical components (CoreDNS, kube-proxy,
#                   metrics-server, Traefik, kube-vip) need broad connectivity and
#                   run partly hostNetwork; locking it down on K3s is risky and
#                   out of scope. Pods in OTHER namespaces still reach kube-dns
#                   because DNS egress is explicitly allowed below.
#   - Probes:       kubelet liveness/readiness probes (node-to-pod) are exempt
#                   from NetworkPolicy — node-originated traffic is not enforced.
#   - Admission     webhooks (cert-manager, metallb) are called by the kube-apiserver,
#                   which runs as a host process (not a pod) — that traffic is also
#                   node-originated and therefore exempt, so the deny-ingress below
#                   does NOT break webhook validation.
#   - hostNetwork:  kube-router does NOT enforce NP on hostNetwork pods. The Ceph
#                   CSI node plugins and the MetalLB speakers run hostNetwork, so the
#                   ceph-csi-operator-system / metallb-system policies only apply to
#                   the operator/controller/provisioner pods (which is what we protect
#                   — they hold the Ceph Secret / drive provisioning / manage
#                   allocations), not to the speakers/node plugins themselves.
# ============================================================

# 1. default — strict quarantine. A pod that lands here can only resolve DNS;
#    it cannot be reached and cannot reach anything else. Deploy real apps in a
#    dedicated namespace (see README), not in `default`.
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: default-deny-all
  namespace: default
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
    - Egress
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-dns-egress
  namespace: default
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: kube-system
          podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              k8s-app: kube-dns
      ports:
        - protocol: UDP
          port: 53
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 53
---
# 2. metallb-system — deny all, then let the controller reach the API server
#    (leader election + watch) and DNS. Speakers run hostNetwork (not enforced);
#    the controller's webhook is served to the kube-apiserver (node-origin,
#    exempt — see header). Nothing else legitimately reaches MetalLB pods.
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: default-deny-all
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
    - Egress
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-egress-kubeapi
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - ipBlock:
            cidr: {{ node_cidr }}
      ports:
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 6443
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-egress-dns
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: kube-system
          podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              k8s-app: kube-dns
      ports:
        - protocol: UDP
          port: 53
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 53
---
# 3. ceph-csi-operator-system — deny all, then let the operator + provisioner
#    (ctrlplugin) reach the Ceph cluster, the API server and DNS. The CSI
#    provisioner connects to the Ceph monitors AND to the OSDs directly (after
#    fetching the OSD map), so the allow targets the whole ceph_subnet, not just
#    the monitor IPs. Ports: mon msgr2 3300, mon msgr1 6789, OSDs/mgrs 6800-7300
#    (endPort — supported by kube-router). Node plugins run hostNetwork (not
#    enforced); this protects the operator + ctrlplugin, which hold the Ceph
#    Secret and drive RBD/CephFS provisioning.
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: default-deny-all
  namespace: ceph-csi-operator-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
    - Egress
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-egress-ceph
  namespace: ceph-csi-operator-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - ipBlock:
            cidr: {{ ceph_subnet }}
      ports:
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 3300
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 6789
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 6800
          endPort: 7300
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-egress-kubeapi
  namespace: ceph-csi-operator-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - ipBlock:
            cidr: {{ node_cidr }}
      ports:
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 6443
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-egress-dns
  namespace: ceph-csi-operator-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: kube-system
          podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              k8s-app: kube-dns
      ports:
        - protocol: UDP
          port: 53
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 53